    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overflow in dft8192 implementation causing incorrect FFT results\n\n### Summary\nThe dft8192 function in the OpenAirInterface 5G codebase contains a buffer overflow bug that causes incorrect FFT computation results. The ytmp array was declared with insufficient size (1024 elements) but the implementation attempts to write 2048 elements to it during processing.\n\nThis manifests as corrupted FFT outputs, particularly noticeable in downlink processing where 8192-point DFTs are used for PRACH detection.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts_neon.c`: Increased ytmp array size from 1024 to 2048 elements in dft8192 function to match the actual memory requirements.\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce this issue:\n1. Run a scenario that uses 8192-point DFT operations (e.g., PRACH detection with long preamble formats)\n2. Observe corrupted frequency domain outputs or false PRACH detections\n3. Memory sanitizer tools will detect out-of-bounds writes in the dft8192 function\n\nThe fix ensures that when two 4096-point DFTs are computed and stored at ytmp and ytmp+1024 offsets, there is sufficient buffer space allocated.\n\n"
}